To calculate the total number of variations on a 3x4 table, we need to use combinatorics. We can use the formula C(n+k-1, k), which gives the number of combinations of n things taken k at a time. In this case, we have 3 rows and 4 columns, so n = 3 and k = 4. Plugging these values into the formula gives us C(3+4-1, 4) = C(6, 4) = 15. Therefore, there are 15 possible variations on a 3x4 table.

