Binary search works by dividing the search interval in half each time until it finds the searched element or determines that it is not present. The search starts by comparing the middle element of the interval with the target element. If they match, then the search is complete. Otherwise, if the target element is less than the middle element, then the lower half of the interval becomes the new search interval. If the target element is greater than the middle element, then the upper half of the interval becomes the new search interval. This process is repeated until the search finds the target element or establishes that it is not present.

Here is a JavaScript implementation of the binary search algorithm:
```javascript
function binarySearch(arr, target) {
  let left = 0;
  let right = arr.length - 1;
  while (left <= right) {
    const mid = Math.floor((left + right) / 2);
    if (arr[mid] === target) {
      return mid;
    } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
      left = mid + 1;
    } else {
      right = mid - 1;
    }
  }
  return -1;
}
```

To use this implementation, you can pass the sorted array and the target element as arguments to the binarySearch function. For example:
```javascript
const arr = [1, 3, 5, 7, 9];
console.log(binarySearch(arr, 3)); // Output: 1
